The fluorescence emission peak of GQDs (A) and GQDs-APTES (B) is shown in Fig. 7
                        . When the GQDs-APTES were stimulated at 340 nm, an asymmetric fluorescence emission peak at 450 nm developed, as seen. These findings show that the silica coating is optically clear and does not impair the photoluminescence properties of GQDs [39]. The GQDs-encased in MIP probe can be used to detect biotin efficiently (Fig. 8
                        ). The fluorescence intensities of non-imprinted composite (black curve) and composite after (blue curve) and before (purple curve) template removal are shown in Fig. 8.

The fluorescence probe's selectivity was tested by comparing the fluorescence response to certain functional and structural counterparts that could interfere, such as ascorbic acid, sucrose, uric acid, and glucose (Fig. 13
                        ). Many particular recognition sites on the surface of MIPs were created during the GQD-encased in MIP synthesis process, and the size, shape, and spatial distribution of these locations were complementary to those of biotin. In this study, there was a clear advantage for biotin over other interferes in composite quenching (Table 4
                        ). When the presence of a substance or ion caused a fluctuation of more than 5% in the sensor fluorescence intensity in the presence of a constant amount of biotin, it was assumed that it was an interfering agent. Furthermore, in order to better understand the specificity of the proposed probe, the fluorescence responses of MIPs for biotin and those interfering were compared to NIPs. Fig. 13 shows that the five analogues quenched the fluorescence intensity of NIPs with a similar effectiveness, which was lower than that of MIPs. These subsequent findings recognize that the high specificity of MIP detection for the templates molecules is mostly due to the particular binding of biotin to MIPs, demonstrating significant application for biotin detection in real samples.
